# Svelte clean code (apps/web)

Stack reality first: this is a **Svelte 5 SPA on Vite** — **not SvelteKit**.
There is no `src/routes/`, no `$lib`, no `load` functions, no form actions, no
SSR. State uses **runes** (`$state`, `$derived`, `$effect`), not the legacy
`$:` label or `export let`. Structural rules (feature folders, `api.ts`
isolation, `lib/shared` vs `features/shared`, client-side-only permission
checks) live in `frontend-architecture.mdc` and `ARCHITECTURE.md` Part 2 —
this rule is only about writing clean code within that structure.

## Components

- Keep components small and single-responsibility. When a component grows past
  a few hundred lines or juggles several unrelated concerns (e.g. a multi-step
  wizard), split the sub-parts into child components under the owning feature's
  `components/` folder and let the parent hold orchestration + state.
- Pass state to children with `$bindable()` props or explicit callback props —
  don't reach into a child's internals.
- Presentational, cross-feature primitives (Alert/banner, form field, button)
  belong in `features/shared/` (that is where the existing shared components
  live); domain-specific components stay in their owning feature.

## Keep complex logic out of the markup layer

- Pure, testable logic (payload shaping, parsing, branching decisions, error
  classification) goes in a colocated `*-logic.ts` next to the component, not
  inline in the `<script>`. Follow the existing pattern, e.g.
  `features/calendar/calendar-wizard-logic.ts`.
- The component's job is: hold `$state`, call `api.ts`, call logic helpers,
  render. If a handler is doing real computation, extract it.

## Reactivity

- Prefer `$derived` for values computed from other state — never recompute
  manually or mirror state into a second `$state` you keep in sync by hand.
- Use `$effect` only for genuine side effects (not for deriving values). Don't
  add reactivity that isn't needed.

## Naming

- Descriptive names; no single letters except loop indices.
- Prefix event handlers with `handle` (`handleSubmit`, `handleAddClosure`).
- Boolean-returning helpers/vars use `is`/`has`/`can` (`isDraftNotFoundError`).

## State / stores

- Keep stores focused and single-purpose — one concern per store (as already
  done: `session`, `teacher-context`, `school-scope`, `support-session`,
  `assignment-load-gate`). Never grow one god-store holding unrelated slices;
  it forces needless re-renders and hurts readability.

## Don't repeat yourself

- Repeated boilerplate (e.g. `err instanceof Error ? err.message : 'fallback'`)
  belongs in a shared helper (`lib/shared/errors.ts` → `toErrorMessage`), not
  copy-pasted into every handler.

## Testing (definition of done)

- Behavior changes need Vitest coverage: unit tests for pure `*-logic.ts`
  helpers and stores, component tests for interactive UI with branching. Mock
  the feature's `api.ts` — never hit the real API. Test observable behavior,
  not mock call counts. Run `pnpm --filter @eduai/web test` before claiming
  done. See `testing.mdc`.

## Do NOT

- Do not introduce SvelteKit conventions (`+page.svelte`, `load`, `$lib`,
  server routes) — wrong framework for this app.
- Do not adopt a flat `components/ stores/ services/` split at the app root;
  this app is organized as vertical feature slices (see
  `frontend-architecture.mdc`).
- Do not use `$:` reactive labels or `export let` in new code — use runes.
